---
description: Minimal deterministic workflow for issue creation, planning, implementation, ask mode, and tiny direct changes.
alwaysApply: true
---

# Core Workflow

## 1) Create Issue
- Treat issue creation as capture of a raw idea.
- Keep wording close to the user text.
- Apply only light grammar/clarity cleanup.
- Do not ask clarifying questions at issue creation.
- Do not generate full specs in this stage.
- When the user says "create an issue", create a real GitHub issue in the current repository (not only a draft in chat).
- Use `gh issue create` by default and return the created issue URL.
- If critical fields are missing (title/body), ask only for those missing fields.
- If `gh` is unavailable or not authenticated, resolve installation/authentication first, then create the issue.
- After creating the issue, set state label to `state:created` and remove any other `state:*` labels.

## 2) Plan Issue
- Planning is the main thinking stage.
- Planning is the highest-priority quality gate in this workflow.
- For planning, use the highest-reasoning model available.
- Prefer deeper analysis in planning than in implementation (more repo reading, trade-off analysis, and risk checks).
- Read the repository before proposing a plan.
- Identify impacted files and frontend/backend surfaces.
- Ask clarifying questions before finalizing the plan when needed.
- Do not implement during planning.
- If the user says "Plan issue #<N>", plan the actual GitHub issue number `<N>` in the current repository.
- Use `gh issue view <N>` to fetch issue details when needed.
- Include the issue number and URL in the plan output.
- After finalizing the plan, post it to the same issue as a markdown comment using `gh issue comment <N> --body ...`.
- When planning starts for an issue, set state label to `state:planned` and remove any other `state:*` labels.
- Use this markdown structure for issue plan comments:
  - `## Plan`
  - `## Affected Files`
  - `## Documentation Impact`
  - `## Open Questions`
  - `## Risks`
- If issue fetch or comment posting fails, report the failure clearly and provide the full markdown plan in chat for manual posting.

## 3) Implement Issue
- Implement only after plan approval.
- Before starting new work, check branch/PR freshness:
  - If current branch has a PR that is `merged` or `closed`, do not continue on that branch.
  - Create a new feature branch from latest `master` and open a new PR for new commits.
  - Keep one active change stream per branch/PR pair.
- If the user says "Implement issue #<N>", implement the actual GitHub issue number `<N>` in the current repository.
- Use the latest approved plan from that issue's comments as the implementation source of truth.
- Do not implement unless the issue has label `state:planned`.
- If no approved plan exists on the issue, do not implement; switch to planning flow first.
- If multiple plan comments exist, use the newest explicitly approved one; otherwise ask which plan to apply.
- If multiple `state:*` labels are present, normalize to exactly one state label before proceeding.
- Keep implementation aligned to that plan; if scope changes are needed, update the plan comment before coding.
- Before coding, move issue state from `state:planned` to `state:in-progress`.
- Create a feature branch before coding.
- Follow existing repository patterns.
- Keep changes minimal, focused, and clean.
- Documentation is part of done: update docs whenever behavior, requirements, or acceptance criteria change.
- Use canonical docs only:
  - `docs/requirements/requirements.md`
  - `docs/specs/spec-*.md`
  - `docs/specs/index.md` (when index/coverage changes)
- Open a PR after implementation.
- In every PR, include `## Documentation Impact` with either:
  - updated doc file paths, or
  - `No doc changes needed` with a short reason.
- Include issue closing reference (for example `Closes #123`) when applicable.
- When PR is open, set issue state label to `state:in-review`.
- When merged/closed, set issue state label to `state:done` only after documentation impact is satisfied.
- If blocked, set `state:blocked` and do not continue implementation until unblocked.

## Issue Labels
- Keep exactly one active state label on each issue:
  - `state:created`
  - `state:planned`
  - `state:in-progress`
  - `state:in-review`
  - `state:done`
  - `state:blocked`
- Use one type label when applicable:
  - `type:bug`
  - `type:feature`
  - `type:chore`
- Update labels on each workflow transition and remove superseded state labels.
- Missing type labels are non-blocking warnings, not implementation blockers.

## 4) Ask About Repo
- Provide repository-aware answers and explanations.
- Do not make code changes unless explicitly requested.

## 5) Direct Implement (Tiny Tasks)
- Direct implement is allowed only for very small, obvious, low-risk changes (see `tiny-direct-implement.mdc`).
- Direct implement may skip Create Issue + Plan Issue, but still uses the same delivery discipline:
  - feature branch
  - PR
  - include `Closes #X` when an issue exists
